Solving this system of equations will give us the values of a and b, which will allow us to write the function:

From equation 1: a = -213 + 10b
Substituting this into equations 2, 3, 4, and 5:

167 = (-213 + 10b) + 9b
67 = (-213 + 10b) + 4b
-73 = (-213 + 10b) - 3b
387 = (-213 + 10b) + 20b

Simplifying these equations:

167 = -213 + 19b
67 = -213 + 14b
-73 = -213 + 7b
387 = -213 + 30b

We can write these equations as a matrix equation:
⎡1   -19⎤     ⎡-213⎤     ⎡167⎤
⎢1   -14⎥  *  ⎢-213⎥  =  ⎢67 ⎥
⎢1   -7 ⎥     ⎢-213⎥     ⎢-73 ⎥
⎣1   -30⎦     ⎣-213⎦     ⎣387⎦

Using matrix inversion to solve for the coefficients:
⎡a⎤     ⎡1   -19⎤^(-1)    ⎡-213⎤     ⎡167⎤
⎢ ⎥  =  ⎢1   -14⎥      *  ⎢-213⎥  =  ⎢67 ⎥
⎢b⎥     ⎢1   -7 ⎥         ⎢-213⎥     ⎢-73 ⎥
⎣ ⎦     ⎣1   -30⎦         ⎣-213⎦     ⎣387⎦

Calculating the inverse of the matrix:
⎡1   -19⎤^(-1) = ⎡-8/286⎤
⎢1   -14⎥           ⎢162/286⎥
⎢1   -7 ⎥           ⎢-144/286⎥
⎣1   -30⎦           ⎣276/286⎦

Multiplying the inverse of the matrix by the output values:
⎡a⎤     ⎡-8/286⎤    ⎡-213⎤     ⎡167⎤
⎢ ⎥  =  ⎢162/286⎥  *  ⎢-213⎥  =  ⎢67 ⎥
⎢b⎥     ⎢-144/286⎥    ⎢-213⎥     ⎢-73 ⎥
⎣ ⎦     ⎣276/286⎦    ⎣-213⎦     ⎣387⎦

Calculating the values of a and b:
a = (-8/286)(-213) + (162/286)(-213) + (-144/286)(-213) + (276/286)(-213) = -183.48
b = (-8/286)(167) + (162/286)(67) + (-144/286)(-73) + (276/286)(387) = 10.84

Therefore, the function that captures the relationship between inputs and outputs is:

a + (-10)b = -213

Subtracting the second equation from the first equation:
(-10)b - 4b = -213 - 67
-14b = -280
b = 20

Substituting the value of b in the second equation, we can solve for a:
a + 4(20) = 67
a + 80 = 67
a = -13
